    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-20T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-20T23:00:00-05:00" n="588"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C115/327: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-21T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 21, 1934—12 midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>73. On behalf of the Secretary of Labor thank Butler<note n="7" xml:id="d588fn7"
                        >Harold Butler, director of the International Labor Office.</note> for his
                    telegrams of June 18 and inform him that the United States would welcome <pb
                        facs="0835" n="735" xml:id="pg_735"/> an invitation to join the labor
                    organization. In the absence of an appropriation at the present to cover the
                    expenses connected with the organization we do not contemplate accepting the
                    invitation until we see our way clear to paying our share.</p>
                <p>It would be desirable if steps could now be taken by the International Labor
                    Organization so that if such invitation is accepted the United States could
                    promptly take its place as a member of the Governing Body.</p>
                <p>Miss Perkins also requests that you tell Andrews he may formally transmit the
                    text of the resolution signed by the President on June 19 to the conference or
                    to Butler, as a basis for such action as the conference may take. In the event
                    an invitation is extended the observers should confine themselves to an
                    expression of this Government’s appreciation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
